#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L08_UniversalSet
msgid "The **universal set** §0 is the set of all elements. In Lean,\n"
"§1 is definitionally §2. Every element belongs to it.\n"
"\n"
"This means every set is a subset of §3. After §4,\n"
"the goal becomes §5, which is §6. Use §7 to\n"
"reveal this (retrieving the §8 tactic from Level 1), then close\n"
"the goal.\n"
"\n"
"How do you prove §9? The type §10 has exactly one constructor,\n"
"just like the single-element types you may have seen in the Natural\n"
"Numbers Game. Use §11 — it finds the unique constructor\n"
"and closes the goal.\n"
"\n"
"**New definition**: §12 — the universal set."
msgstr ""

#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L12_ExtWithWork
msgid "Extensionality with Real Work"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `ext`
#. §1: `A = B`
#. §2: `A B : Set α`
#. §3: `ext x`
#. §4: `x : α`
#. §5: `x ∈ A ↔ x ∈ B`
#. §6: `ext x`
#. §7: `x`
#. §8: `ext`
#. §9: `constructor`
#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L11_SetExtensionality
msgid "The §0 tactic proves equality of sets (and other extensional structures)\n"
"by reducing to pointwise equivalence. If the goal is §1 where §2,\n"
"then §3 introduces a fresh variable §4 and changes the goal to\n"
"§5.\n"
"\n"
"## Syntax\n"
"§6 where §7 is the name for the new variable.\n"
"\n"
"## When to use\n"
"Use §8 whenever you need to prove two sets are equal. Follow it with\n"
"§9 to split the resulting iff."
msgstr ""

#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L07_EmptySet
