#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L14_Boss
msgid "# Boss Level\n"
"\n"
"You have learned:\n"
"- §0 and §1 to see through set membership notation\n"
"- §2 to open subset proofs\n"
"- §3 and direct application to use subset hypotheses\n"
"- §4 to split iff statements\n"
"- §5 and §6 to use iff hypotheses\n"
"- §7 to reduce set equality to membership equivalence\n"
"- §8 as a theorem\n"
"\n"
"Now prove the **antisymmetry theorem from scratch**: if §9 and\n"
"§10, then §11. But this time, you may *not* use\n"
"§12 — you must build the proof yourself using §13.\n"
"\n"
"The proof requires you to:\n"
"1. Apply §14 to reduce equality to a pointwise iff.\n"
"2. Split the iff with §15.\n"
"3. In each direction, use the appropriate subset hypothesis.\n"
"\n"
"This integrates the three main skills of the world: extensionality,\n"
"iff splitting, and subset application."
msgstr ""

#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L13_DoubleInclusion
msgid "Double Inclusion"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `show`
#. §1: `hx : x ∈ {y | P y}`
#. §2: `P x`
#. §3: `change`
#. §4: `show`
#. §5: `change`
#. §6: `at`
#. §7: `change`
#. §8: `change P at h`
#. §9: `h`
#. §10: `change`
#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L02_SetBuilderNotation
msgid "In the last level you used §0 to reveal what a set membership goal\n"
"really means. But what about hypotheses? If you have a hypothesis\n"
"§1, it *looks* like set membership, but it\n"
"*is* the proposition §2.\n"
"\n"
"The **§3** tactic lets you replace a goal *or a hypothesis* with a\n"
"definitionally equal expression. Unlike §4 (which only works on the\n"
"goal), §5 can modify hypotheses using the §6 keyword.\n"
"\n"
"**New tactic**: §7 — replaces a goal or hypothesis with a\n"
"definitionally equal form. Use §8 to modify hypothesis §9.\n"
"\n"
"In this level, you have a hypothesis about membership in a set-builder\n"
"set, and you need to use it to prove membership in a different set.\n"
"Use §10 to reveal what both sides really mean, then finish the proof."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `norm_num`
#. §1: `2 + 3 = 5`
#. §2: `7 > 3`
#: Game.Metadata
msgid "§0 is an automation tactic that closes numeric goals\n"
"like §1 or §2. It is disabled in this course to\n"
"ensure you engage with the proof structure rather than relying on\n"
"automation."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `show`
#. §1: `x ∈ S`
#. §2: `S`
#. §3: `show P x`
#. §4: `show <expression>`
#. §5: `show`
#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L01_WhatIsASet
msgid "The §0 tactic replaces the current goal with a definitionally equal expression.\n"
"If your goal is §1 where §2 is defined as a set-builder set, you can write\n"
"§3 to see the underlying predicate directly.\n"
"\n"
"## Syntax\n"
"§4\n"
"\n"
"## When to use\n"
"Use §5 when the goal is technically correct but displayed in a form that\n"
"makes the next step unclear. This is common with set membership goals."
msgstr ""

#: GameServer.RpcHandlers
msgid "level completed with warnings… 🎭"
msgstr ""

