#. §1: `B`
#. §2: `A ⊆ B`
#. §3: `A`
#. §4: `B`
#. §5: `A ⊆ B`
#. §6: `∀ x, x ∈ A → x ∈ B`
#. §7: `x`
#. §8: `x`
#. §9: `A`
#. §10: `x`
#. §11: `B`
#. §12: `∀`
#. §13: `→`
#. §14: `intro x`
#. §15: `intro hx`
#. §16: `x ∈ A`
#. §17: `x ∈ B`
#. §18: `⊆`
#. §19: `A ⊆ B`
#. §20: `∀ x, x ∈ A → x ∈ B`
#. §21: `⊂`
#. §22: `A ⊆ B ∧ A ≠ B`
#. §23: `⊆`
#. §24: `A ⊆ A`
#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L03_SubsetProofs
msgid "A set §0 is a **subset** of §1, written §2, when every element\n"
"of §3 is also an element of §4. In Lean, §5 unfolds to:\n"
"\n"
"§6\n"
"\n"
"That is: for every §7, if §8 is in §9, then §10 is in §11.\n"
"\n"
"Since this is a §12 statement followed by an §13, the standard approach\n"
"is: §14 to name the element, then §15 to assume §16,\n"
"and finally prove §17.\n"
"\n"
"In this level, you will prove that every set is a subset of itself.\n"
"This is the simplest possible subset proof, but it establishes the\n"
"fundamental pattern: **intro the element, intro the membership\n"
"hypothesis, then prove the goal**.\n"
"\n"
"**New definitions**: §18 — subset relation on sets. §19 means\n"
"§20.\n"
"\n"
"**Note**: Lean also has §21 (strict subset, meaning §22),\n"
"but we will not use it in this course. When we write §23, equality is\n"
"allowed — §24 is always true."
msgstr ""

