#. §0: `ext`
#. §1: `A = B`
#. §2: `A`
#. §3: `B`
#. §4: `x ∈ A ↔ x ∈ B`
#. §5: `x`
#. §6: `ext x`
#. §7: `constructor`
#. §8: `ext x`
#. §9: `constructor`
#. §10: `ext`
#. §11: `Set.ext_iff`
#. §12: `A = B ↔ ∀ x, x ∈ A ↔ x ∈ B`
#: Game.Levels.SetsAndMembership.L11_SetExtensionality
msgid "Here is the most important idea in this world: **two sets are equal if\n"
"and only if they have the same elements.** This principle is called\n"
"**set extensionality**.\n"
"\n"
"In Lean, the **§0** tactic turns a goal of the form §1 (where\n"
"§2 and §3 are sets) into the goal §4 for a fresh\n"
"variable §5. After §6, you have an iff to prove, which you\n"
"split with §7 and handle each direction.\n"
"\n"
"This gives us the fundamental proof pattern for set equality:\n"
"\n"
"1. §8 — reduce equality to membership equivalence\n"
"2. §9 — split the iff into forward and backward\n"
"3. Prove each direction as an implication\n"
"\n"
"This pattern — **ext, constructor, chase** — will be used hundreds of\n"
"times in this course. Master it here.\n"
"\n"
"**New tactic**: §10 — reduces set equality to elementwise equivalence.\n"
"\n"
"**New theorem**: §11 — states §12."
msgstr ""

